\begin_layout Subsubsection
Multi-fluid Solutions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Multi-fluid, single column simulations are initialised by horizontally and
 conditionally averaging the full resolution single fluid initial conditions.
 Sinking air is put into fluid zero and rising air into fluid one.
 The velocity field after one time step is used for initialising the partition
 as the air is stationary at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=0$
\end_inset

.
 Results are shown in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:multiFluidSingleColumn"

\end_inset

 for various assumptions about transfers between fluids and various pressure
 differences between fluids.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If there is no drag between fluids, no transfers, no diffusion and the pressures
 of both fluids are assumed equal then the multi-fluid equations are unstable
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "TEB19"

\end_inset

.
 The simulation with no transfers (
\begin_inset Formula $S_{ij}=0$
\end_inset

) in the top row of figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:multiFluidSingleColumn"

\end_inset

 is shown at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=500\ \text{s}$
\end_inset

 and it run for 700s before crashing.
 At 
\begin_inset Formula $t=500\ \text{s}$
\end_inset

 the buoyant fluid has risen very little from the initial conditions and
 oscillations have developed in all fields.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 oscillates between zero and one meaning that only one fluid is present
 at some locations so there is no possibility for the fluids to move past
 each other.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The pressure difference between fluids is parameterised using the divergence
 local to a fluid.
 Using 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{i}=P-\gamma\nabla\cdot\mathbf{u}_{i}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma=4\times10^{3}\text{m}^{2}\text{s}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 stabilises the solution and the resulting pressure gradients force the
 two fluids to move past each other.
 Results, shown in the second row of figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:multiFluidSingleColumn"

\end_inset

, are stable but not realistic, with a discontinuity with no fluid 1 below
 the buoyant fluid and very little falling air at the lowest height of the
 rising fluid.
 With a single column and two fluids, all air must rise in one fluid and
 sink in the other.
 Continuity does not allow for any other solution.
 Pressure gradients can accelerate or decelerate this flow but as the model
 is set up, with no transfers between fluids, no fluid can be change direction.
 It is therefore essential to have transfers between fluids.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Divergence will not only lead to pressure differences between the fluids,
 it will also force changes in vertical direction; if rising air decelerates,
 this is associated with convergence and air will stop rising and some will
 need to sink to obey continuity.
 This can be parameterised by setting an entrainment rate equal to the fluid
 divergence: 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{ij}=-\nabla\cdot\mathbf{u}_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Simulating the rising bubble with 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{ij}=-\nabla\cdot\mathbf{u}_{i}$
\end_inset

 and without pressure differences between the fluids is sufficient to stabilise
 the numerical solution (third row of figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:multiFluidSingleColumn"

\end_inset

); fluid is detrained behind the bubble, leaving buoyant air in fluid zero
 near the ground and a small fraction continues to rise with a discontinuity
 and possible instability at the bubble front; the buoyancy force is producing
 vertical motion but there is no pressure to make it smooth.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Once we use entrainment and detrainment set by divergence (
\begin_inset Formula $S_{ij}=-\nabla\cdot\mathbf{u}_{i}$
\end_inset

) and pressure difference between the fluids controlled by divergence (
\begin_inset Formula $P_{i}=P-\gamma\nabla\cdot\mathbf{u}_{i}$
\end_inset

) simulations are more realistic (fourth and fifth rows of figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:multiFluidSingleColumn"

\end_inset

).
 The detrainment of buoyant fluid leads to smooth profiles behind the bubble
 although 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{1}$
\end_inset

 is lower than the resolved simulation in the lower half of the domain and
 the fluid left behind is too warm.
 This is expected since the detrained fluid is assumed to have the mean
 fluid properties of the fluid it is leaving whereas in reality the least
 buoyant fluid will leaving the rising fluid and start to fall.
 Transferring non-mean properties is the subject of future research and
 should depend on models of sub-grid-scale variability within each fluid.
 Using 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{ij}=-\nabla\cdot\mathbf{u}_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{i}=P-\gamma\nabla\cdot\mathbf{u}_{i}$
\end_inset

, the bubble rises to approximately the same height as the resolved single
 fluid simulation, peak vertical velocity is approximately correct although
 it is above rather than below the most buoyant part of the bubble and different
 pressures between the fluids keep profiles smooth although the large negative
 pressure gradient below the bubble in the rising fluid is not simulated.
 Results using two different values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 are shown which give pressure gradients slightly less than those of the
 resolved simulation.
 Larger values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 slow down the bubble rise unrealistically.
 There appears to be another process that we are missing than leads to the
 negative pressure gradients behind the bubble that accelerate the rise
 or the detrainment behind the bubble is removing divergence that would
 otherwise lead to the necessary pressure gradients.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are clearly discrepancies between the single fluid resolved rising
 bubble and the two fluid single column rising bubble but we do wish aim
 to over-fit the multi-fluid model to one, dry, two-dimensional test case.
 Key features of this test case have been reproduced so other test cases
 should be considered.
\end_layout

